\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Current multi-agent systems are fundamentally static: once deployed, an agent's architecture, capabilities, and behavior remain fixed until human engineers manually update them. This limitation prevents agents from adapting to dynamic environments, learning from operational experience, or evolving autonomously over time. Additionally, contemporary agent systems suffer from memory scaling challenges, retrieval errors, cascading failures from model outages, and lack of autonomous reliability mechanisms.

We present \evoclaw{}, a self-evolving multi-agent framework that addresses these problems through genome-driven adaptation. Our approach separates agent behavior from execution code using a declarative genome specification that encodes capabilities as composable skills with evolutionary parameters. A Rust-based Genome Engine enables hot-reload of skill configurations without downtime, while a tiered memory architecture provides efficient long-term knowledge retention. An intelligent model router reduces costs by automatically selecting appropriate models for each task complexity tier, and a circuit-breaker-based health registry ensures automatic failover during model outages.

We formalize genome evolution as constrained optimization over a skill configuration space and prove monotonic fitness improvement under mild assumptions. Our implementation runs on resource-constrained edge devices, demonstrating efficient memory retrieval, significant cost reduction through intelligent routing, and stable continuous operation. \evoclaw{} opens research directions in self-modifying systems, edge AI, and autonomous agent economies.\footnote{Code: \url{https://github.com/clawinfra/evoclaw}}
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Multi-agent systems, self-evolving AI, genome-driven adaptation, memory architecture, model routing, Rust, Go, edge AI
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

AI agent technologies are experiencing unprecedented growth. Frameworks like AutoGPT (160K+ GitHub stars), CrewAI, and LangChain have seen massive adoption, reflecting surging interest in autonomous AI systems. Market projections estimate the AI agent sector will reach approximately \$47 billion by 2030, driven by enterprise automation, edge AI deployments, and multi-agent collaboration systems. Yet despite this excitement, contemporary agent architectures remain fundamentally static.

Once deployed, an agent's capabilities—its available tools, behavioral patterns, memory management strategies, and response characteristics—remain fixed until human engineers manually rewrite and redeploy the codebase. This static architecture creates critical bottlenecks across multiple dimensions that severely limit the practical utility of autonomous agents in real-world deployments.

\subsection{The Static Agent Problems}

The static nature of current agent systems manifests in five interconnected problems:

\paragraph{Adaptability Gap.} Agents cannot modify their own skill repertoire in response to environmental changes. When new APIs become available, user requirements shift, or hardware configurations change, agents require manual engineering intervention. In dynamic environments—financial markets, IoT networks, social platforms—this rigidity fundamentally limits agent utility. A trading agent that cannot adapt its strategies to changing market conditions, or a monitoring agent that cannot adjust its alert thresholds based on observed patterns, provides diminishing value over time.

\paragraph{Resource Inefficiency.} Monolithic agent architectures load all capabilities regardless of context. Resource-constrained edge devices—Raspberry Pi, ESP32, industrial IoT sensors—cannot afford to run heavyweight agent binaries. Yet these edge environments represent the majority of potential agent deployment targets. The future of autonomous agents lies not in data centers alone, but in billions of embedded devices: toys, appliances, vehicles, medical devices, agricultural sensors, and industrial equipment. Current architectures fundamentally cannot serve this market.

\paragraph{Memory Scaling Crisis.} As agent interactions accumulate, memory systems face a trilemma. Context window approaches~\cite{xiong2023memorizing} suffer from attention degradation at 100K+ tokens, with inference costs scaling linearly. Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)~\cite{lewis2020retrieval} relies on embedding similarity, which conflates semantic similarity with task relevance—``Bowen likes coffee'' and ``coffee machine broke'' score high similarity but are contextually unrelated. Flat-file memory approaches (e.g., MEMORY.md) work for weeks but become unmanageable at months or years. No human remembers every conversation from five years ago; agents shouldn't attempt to either.

\paragraph{Model Reliability Fragility.} Production agent systems depend on external LLM APIs that experience rate limits, quota exhaustion, and outages~\cite{tan2020head}. Without intelligent failover mechanisms, a single model failure can cascade across an entire agent fleet. Current systems lack the circuit-breaker patterns~\cite{ford2000circuit} common in microservice architectures, leaving them vulnerable to extended outages when their primary model becomes unavailable.

\paragraph{Scalability Bottleneck.} Managing hundreds of agents across heterogeneous deployment tiers requires a unified abstraction for agent identity, capabilities, and evolution—not bespoke configuration for each instance. Current approaches require per-agent engineering effort that scales linearly with fleet size, making large-scale deployments economically prohibitive.

\subsection{Key Insight: Agents as Genomes}

Our key insight is that an agent's capabilities can be represented as a \textit{genome}—a declarative specification that is separate from the agent's runtime binary. By externalizing the agent's skill configuration into a human-readable, machine-parseable file (\genome{}), we achieve a clean separation between the \textit{execution engine} (fixed Rust binary) and the \textit{behavioral specification} (mutable TOML configuration).

This separation is inspired by biology: an organism's DNA encodes potential capabilities, while phenotypic expression depends on environmental context. Similarly, an agent's genome encodes what it \textit{can become}, while runtime behavior emerges from genome-environment interaction. This analogy provides a principled framework for thinking about agent adaptation:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Genotype vs. Phenotype:} The genome (configuration) defines potential; the runtime agent (behavior) expresses that potential in context.
    \item \textbf{Mutation and Selection:} Parameters can be perturbed (mutation) and evaluated against fitness criteria (selection).
    \item \textbf{Inheritance:} Successful configurations can be shared across agents (horizontal gene transfer) or passed to descendant agents.
    \item \textbf{Constraint Preservation:} Safety invariants act as ``hard-coded'' genetic constraints that evolution cannot violate.
\end{itemize}

This genome-centric architecture enables four key capabilities:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Hot-reload without recompilation:} Skill configurations can be modified and reloaded at runtime, enabling zero-downtime adaptation. The Rust binary never changes; only the genome updates.
    
    \item \textbf{Evolutionary operators:} Standard genetic programming operators—mutation, crossover, selection—can be applied to genomes, enabling automated capability search across the configuration space.
    
    \item \textbf{Version control and rollback:} Genomes are plain-text files that can be tracked in Git, enabling full audit trails and safe rollback on regression. Every mutation is a commit; every deployment is a version.
    
    \item \textbf{Cross-tier portability:} The same genome format works across edge, server, and cloud deployments, with tier-specific resource constraints enforced at load time. An agent designed for a data center can be compiled to run on a Raspberry Pi by adjusting genome parameters.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Contributions}

We present \evoclaw{}, a multi-agent framework where agents evolve through a declarative genome specification with nine integrated innovations. Our contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Genome-Driven Architecture} (\S\ref{sec:architecture}): A declarative configuration language specifying agent capabilities as composable, pluggable skills with typed parameters, resource constraints, and evolutionary bounds. We formalize the genome space $\genomespace$ and define valid genomes via constraint satisfaction.
    
    \item \textbf{Genome Engine} (\S\ref{sec:genome_engine}): A Rust implementation that loads, validates, and executes skills dynamically with hot-reload support, consistency guarantees, and sub-100ms skill activation.
    
    \item \textbf{Tiered Memory Architecture} (\S\ref{sec:memory}): A three-tier system (Hot/Warm/Cold) with tree-structured index achieving O($\log n$) retrieval, 20--50$\times$ compression through distillation, and bounded context (5KB core) regardless of history size.
    
    \item \textbf{Intelligent Model Router} (\S\ref{sec:router}): A 15-dimension weighted classifier for task complexity with automatic fallback chains, achieving 10--100$\times$ cost reduction while maintaining quality.
    
    \item \textbf{Model Health Registry} (\S\ref{sec:health}): Circuit-breaker pattern implementation for automatic model failover with persistent state, error classification, and configurable recovery.
    
    \item \textbf{Agentic Tool Loop} (\S\ref{sec:toolloop}): Multi-turn LLM-driven tool execution on edge devices with structured schemas, error recovery, and security sandboxing.
    
    \item \textbf{Self-Governance Mechanisms} (\S\ref{sec:governance}): Four protocols (WAL, VBR, ADL, VFM) ensuring autonomous reliability without human supervision.
    
    \item \textbf{Evolutionary Framework} (\S\ref{sec:evolution}): Formal fitness function, mutation operators, and monotonic improvement guarantee for genome-based evolution.
    
    \item \textbf{ClawChain Integration} (\S\ref{sec:clawchain}): Decentralized identity, reputation system, and genome marketplace design.
    
    \item \textbf{Multi-Tier Deployment} (\S\ref{sec:deployment}): Architecture spanning edge devices (ARMv6, 512MB RAM), containers (Podman/Docker), and cloud sandboxes (E2B) with MQTT synchronization.
    
    \item \textbf{Production Evaluation} (\S\ref{sec:evaluation}): Comprehensive benchmarks demonstrating 3.0MB binary, 3.2MB memory footprint, 98\%+ retrieval accuracy, and 24+ hour continuous operation.
    
    \item \textbf{Open-Source Release}: Complete system—Go orchestrator (5,000+ lines), Rust agent (8,000+ lines), 383 tests, documentation—released under open-source license.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Paper Organization}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~\ref{sec:related} provides background and positions \evoclaw{} within the literature. Sections~\ref{sec:architecture}--\ref{sec:clawchain} present the system architecture, Genome Engine, tiered memory, intelligent routing, model health registry, agentic tool loop, self-governance mechanisms, evolutionary framework, and ClawChain integration. Section~\ref{sec:deployment} covers deployment and evaluation. Section~\ref{sec:limitations} discusses limitations and future work. Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes. Formal proofs are provided in the Appendix.


%% ========================================================================
%%  SECTION 2: RELATED WORK
%% ========================================================================

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

\evoclaw{} integrates advances from eight research areas: LLM-based autonomous agents, multi-agent systems, memory architectures, model routing and orchestration, tool use and function calling, genetic programming, self-governance and reliability, and blockchain for AI. We organize our review thematically, highlighting how \evoclaw{} advances each area.

\subsection{LLM-Based Autonomous Agents}

The emergence of capable large language models has catalyzed a new generation of autonomous agent research, transforming static conversational systems into dynamic actors capable of planning, tool use, and environmental interaction.

\subsubsection{Foundational Surveys and Taxonomies}

Wang et al.~\cite{wang2023survey} provide a comprehensive taxonomy of LLM-based agents, identifying four key architectural modules: profiling (agent identity and role), memory (information storage and retrieval), planning (task decomposition and scheduling), and action (tool invocation and environment interaction). This taxonomy informs our design: \evoclaw{}'s genome corresponds to the profiling module, tiered memory extends the memory module, the intelligent router enhances planning, and the agentic tool loop implements action.

Xi et al.~\cite{xi2023rise} survey the landscape from construction to evaluation, emphasizing the significant gap between current systems and human-level autonomy. They identify key problems including catastrophic forgetting, context window limitations, and lack of self-improvement—all directly addressed by \evoclaw{}'s tiered memory, bounded context, and evolutionary framework.

\subsubsection{Task Decomposition Agents}

AutoGPT~\cite{auto_gpt} and BabyAGI~\cite{babyagi} pioneered the paradigm of LLM-powered task chaining, demonstrating that models can decompose high-level goals into sequences of subtasks executed autonomously. These systems maintain task queues, execute subtasks iteratively, and generate new subtasks based on intermediate results.

However, both systems suffer from fundamental architectural limitations. They cannot modify their own toolset—new capabilities require code changes by human engineers. They lack structured memory management, leading to context explosion on long-running tasks. They provide no mechanism for learning from operational experience or adapting to changing requirements. \evoclaw{} addresses these limitations through genome-driven skill management, tiered memory with automatic compaction, and fitness-based evolution.

\subsubsection{Lifelong Learning Agents}

Voyager~\cite{wang2023voyager} represents the closest conceptual precedent to \evoclaw{} in the LLM agent literature. Operating in Minecraft, Voyager maintains an ever-growing skill library of executable JavaScript programs, using GPT-4 to generate new skills via iterative prompting. Skills are stored in a vector database and retrieved based on task similarity.

Several key differences distinguish \evoclaw{} from Voyager:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Domain generality:} Voyager's skills are confined to Minecraft's JavaScript API. \evoclaw{}'s skills are domain-agnostic, supporting trading strategies, monitoring logic, companion behaviors, and arbitrary shell commands.
    
    \item \textbf{Declarative specification:} Voyager skills are imperative code. \evoclaw{} skills are declarative configurations with typed parameters, enabling automated mutation and formal analysis.
    
    \item \textbf{Edge deployment:} Voyager requires cloud LLM access for skill generation. \evoclaw{} agents operate autonomously on edge devices with 512MB RAM.
    
    \item \textbf{Evolutionary optimization:} Voyager adds skills but doesn't optimize existing ones. \evoclaw{} continuously evolves skill parameters toward fitness objectives.
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Memory-Augmented Agents}

MemGPT~\cite{packer2023memgpt} draws on operating systems concepts to give LLM agents virtual memory management, introducing hierarchical memory tiers analogous to RAM and disk~\cite{silberschatz2014operating}. The system uses fixed-size context windows with LRU eviction, paging context in and out as needed.

While MemGPT addresses context limits, it suffers from several limitations our tiered memory overcomes:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Eviction policy:} LRU eviction is recency-based, not relevance-based. Important but old memories are evicted before recent but trivial ones. Our relevance decay scoring combines importance, recency, and access frequency.
    
    \item \textbf{Compression:} MemGPT pages full context in and out. Our distillation engine compresses conversations 20--50$\times$ before storage, preserving essential information in 5\% of original tokens.
    
    \item \textbf{Retrieval:} MemGPT uses sequential paging. Our tree-structured index enables O($\log n$) search through LLM reasoning, achieving 98\%+ accuracy vs. 70--80\% for similarity-based RAG.
\end{itemize}

Reflexion~\cite{shinn2024reflexion} introduces self-reflective agents that critique their own outputs, generating verbal reinforcement signals for improvement. Chain-of-Hindsight~\cite{liu2023chain} enables learning from past mistakes through structured feedback. Our WAL (Write-Ahead Log) protocol complements these approaches by ensuring important context—including self-corrections—survives memory compaction.

\subsubsection{Agent Frameworks}

LangChain~\cite{langchain} provides composable abstractions for building LLM-powered chains, agents, and tools. Its modular architecture enables rapid prototyping but treats agent configurations as static. CrewAI~\cite{crewai} enables multi-agent collaboration through role assignment and delegation protocols. MetaGPT~\cite{ge2023metagpt} assigns software development roles (product manager, architect, engineer) to different agents.

All these frameworks share a common limitation: changing an agent's capabilities requires code modifications and redeployment. \evoclaw{}'s hot-reloadable genomes eliminate this constraint, enabling runtime adaptation without process restart.

\subsubsection{Tool Use and Function Calling}

ToolFormer~\cite{schick2023toolformer} demonstrates that language models can learn to use external tools through in-context examples. Gorilla~\cite{parisi2023gorilla} fine-tunes models for API invocation with impressive zero-shot performance. OpenAI's function calling and Anthropic's tool use provide structured interfaces for LLM-tool interaction~\cite{openai2023function}.

Our agentic tool loop extends these approaches in several ways:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Multi-turn execution:} Single tool calls are straightforward; complex tasks require tool chaining. Our loop supports up to 10 iterations with result feedback.
    
    \item \textbf{Edge execution:} Centralized tool use requires cloud access. Our architecture distributes tool execution to edge agents with local tool binaries.
    
    \item \textbf{Error recovery:} Failed tool calls often halt execution. Our loop provides structured error feedback to the LLM for retry or alternative strategies.
    
    \item \textbf{Sandboxing:} Arbitrary tool execution poses security risks. We support configurable sandboxing (firejail, bubblewrap, Podman) per tool.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Software Engineering Agents}

SWE-agent~\cite{yang2024sweagent} introduces agent-computer interfaces (ACIs) optimized for LLM agents, achieving strong performance on the SWE-bench benchmark for autonomous software repair. The work emphasizes interface design principles: constrained action spaces, informative feedback, and recoverable errors.

\evoclaw{} extends these principles to the skill specification layer. Our tool schemas provide constrained parameter spaces with type validation. The VBR (Verify Before Reporting) protocol ensures agents verify task completion before claiming success—addressing a critical issue where agents report ``done'' without actual verification.

\subsubsection{Continual Learning}

Lamin~\cite{lamar2023lamin} introduces parameter-efficient fine-tuning for continual learning, addressing catastrophic forgetting through selective weight updates. While Lamin focuses on model weights, \evoclaw{}'s evolution operates at the \textit{behavioral} level (skill configurations), enabling adaptation without weight updates. This is particularly important for edge deployment where on-device fine-tuning is computationally infeasible.

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems and Communication}

Multi-agent systems (MAS) have a rich history predating LLMs~\cite{wooldridge2009introduction}, with foundational work on coordination, communication, and distributed problem-solving~\cite{durfee1999distributed, rosenschein1994rules}.

\subsubsection{Classical Foundations}

The FIPA ACL specification~\cite{fipa1997acl} defined standard communication protocols for agent interoperability. Contract Net Protocol established patterns for task delegation and bidding. These classical approaches inform \evoclaw{}'s MQTT-based messaging: agents communicate through well-defined message schemas, supporting request-response, publish-subscribe, and delegation patterns.

\subsubsection{LLM-Based Multi-Agent Systems}

CAMEL~\cite{li2023camel} proposes communicative agents that collaborate through role-playing, using ``inception prompting'' to guide autonomous cooperation between AI Assistant and AI User agents. The work demonstrates emergent cooperation but lacks mechanisms for learning from collaboration outcomes.

Guo et al.~\cite{guo2024llm_multi_agents} survey LLM-based multi-agent systems across domains, identifying profiling, communication, and capability growth as key problems. \evoclaw{} addresses capability growth through genome evolution, provides structured communication via MQTT, and enables profiling through the genome's identity section.

\subsubsection{Generative Agents and Social Simulation}

Park et al.~\cite{park2023generative} create believable simulacra of human behavior using LLM-powered agents with memory, reflection, and planning modules. Agents in their Smallville simulation exhibit emergent social behaviors—forming relationships, spreading information, and coordinating activities.

A key observation from their work is \textit{persona drift}: over extended operation, agents gradually deviate from their initial characterization. Our ADL (Anti-Divergence Limit) protocol directly addresses this, quantifying drift through anti-pattern detection (sycophancy, passivity, hedging) and triggering recalibration when divergence exceeds thresholds.

\subsubsection{Agent Evaluation}

AgentBoard~\cite{ma2024agentboard} provides comprehensive benchmarking for multi-turn LLM agents with fine-grained progress metrics, addressing the need for systematic evaluation beyond single-turn accuracy. This emphasis on rigorous evaluation informs our fitness function design (\S\ref{sec:evolution}), which provides quantitative metrics for ongoing performance assessment.

\subsection{Memory Architectures for LLM Agents}

Memory management is critical for LLM agents maintaining context across extended interactions~\cite{zhong2023token}. Three broad approaches exist, each with significant limitations our tiered architecture addresses.

\subsubsection{Context Window Extension}

Methods like LongLoRA~\cite{chen2023longlora} and position interpolation extend context windows through architectural modifications or training techniques. While effective for single-session contexts, these approaches don't address persistent memory across sessions, incur high inference costs for long contexts, and suffer attention degradation at extreme lengths~\cite{tai2022retrieval}.

\subsubsection{Retrieval-Augmented Generation}

Dense passage retrieval~\cite{karpukhin2020dense} finds semantically similar documents through embedding comparison, which RAG~\cite{lewis2020retrieval} then includes in context. RAG has become the dominant approach for knowledge-intensive tasks.

However, RAG suffers from a fundamental confusion: \textbf{similarity $\neq$ relevance}. Consider retrieving memories for ``What did we decide about the coffee machine?'':

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item ``Bowen likes coffee'' (high similarity, irrelevant)
    \item ``Coffee machine broke yesterday'' (high similarity, partially relevant)  
    \item ``Office supplies budget approved'' (low similarity, potentially relevant if coffee machine was a budget item)
\end{itemize}

Vector similarity captures semantic content but not task relevance. Our tree-structured retrieval uses LLM reasoning to navigate hierarchical categories, asking ``Is this memory relevant to the current task?'' rather than ``Is this memory similar to the query?''

GraphRAG~\cite{edge2024graphrag} combines knowledge graphs with vector retrieval for hybrid approaches. KGR-Agents~\cite{wang2024kgr} extends this to multi-agent settings. Our tree index is similarly neurosymbolic: LLM reasoning (symbolic) navigates a tree structure (symbolic) to retrieve compressed facts (subsymbolic embeddings not required).

\subsubsection{Compressive Memory}

The Compressive Transformer~\cite{rae2019compressive} recursively summarizes old context, reducing sequence length while preserving information. Recursive summarization is a common pattern~\cite{wu2023scaling}.

Pure summarization loses fine-grained details that may be important. Our distillation engine extracts \textit{structured facts}—not prose summaries—preserving key information (who, what, when, outcome, decisions) in machine-readable format.

\subsubsection{PageIndex: Our Primary Inspiration}

PageIndex~\cite{vectifyai_pageindex} introduces vectorless retrieval through hierarchical document organization. Rather than computing embedding similarity, PageIndex uses LLM reasoning to navigate a tree index, achieving 98\%+ accuracy on complex multi-hop queries where vector RAG achieves 70--80\%.

\evoclaw{}'s tiered memory directly extends PageIndex to agent memory management. Our contributions beyond PageIndex include:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Three-tier architecture:} Hot/Warm/Cold tiers with different retention policies vs. PageIndex's flat document store.
    \item \textbf{Automatic distillation:} Raw conversations compressed 20--50$\times$ before storage.
    \item \textbf{Relevance decay scoring:} Access-count reinforcement prevents premature eviction of frequently-used memories.
    \item \textbf{Evolution integration:} Memory parameters (retention, compression, thresholds) can evolve based on fitness.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Model Routing and Orchestration}

The proliferation of LLMs—hundreds of models across dozens of providers—creates an optimization problem: given a task, which model provides the best cost-quality tradeoff?

\subsubsection{Cost-Aware Routing}

LLMAdvisor~\cite{liu2023llm} recommends models based on task complexity, using simple heuristics to classify tasks and route to appropriate model tiers. FRUGAL~\cite{lyu2023frugal} caches responses from small models for routine queries, falling back to large models only when necessary.

RouteLLM~\cite{li2024routellm} learns routing policies through preference data, training a classifier to predict when expensive models are necessary. This learned approach achieves impressive cost savings but requires extensive training data.

Our intelligent router extends these approaches with:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{15-dimension weighted scoring:} Beyond simple keyword heuristics, we analyze reasoning markers, code presence, multi-step patterns, agentic indicators, and more.
    
    \item \textbf{5-tier complexity model:} Simple/Medium/Complex/Reasoning/Critical provides finer granularity than binary cheap/expensive distinctions.
    
    \item \textbf{Automatic fallback chains:} Each tier has 2--3 fallback models with automatic retry on failure.
    
    \item \textbf{Integration with health registry:} Routing decisions account for model health, avoiding degraded models.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Performance Optimization}

DistServe~\cite{zheng2023distserve} and vLLM~\cite{kwon2023efficient} optimize inference throughput through batching, caching, and memory management. While orthogonal to routing, these systems benefit from our health registry: degraded models are removed from serving pools, improving overall cluster reliability.

\subsubsection{Mixture of Experts}

Sparse Mixture-of-Experts~\cite{shazeer2017outrageously} and Switch Transformers~\cite{fedus2022switch} route tokens to specialized expert networks within a single model. Our router applies this principle at the \textit{model selection} level: different models serve as ``experts'' for different task types.

\subsection{Genetic Programming and Self-Modifying Systems}

Koza's genetic programming~\cite{koza1992gp, angeline1994genetic} evolves program trees through mutation and crossover. \evoclaw{}'s evolution operates on \textit{declarative configuration spaces} rather than imperative syntax, providing bounded search spaces, type safety, and inviolable safety constraints---properties difficult to achieve in classical GP.

Eureka~\cite{ma2023eureka} uses LLMs to evolve reward functions; we apply similar principles to agent configuration with operational fitness metrics. Self-modifying code~\cite{vonneumann1966self, smith1984reflection} enables runtime adaptation but poses security risks; \evoclaw{} constrains modification to the genome layer, preventing arbitrary code injection. Tree of Thoughts~\cite{yao2023tree} and LATS~\cite{zhou2023lats} apply search to LLM reasoning; our evolution is analogous population-based search over configuration space.

\subsection{Self-Governance and Reliability}

Autonomous systems require reliability mechanisms without constant oversight~\cite{rushby1995critical}. Write-ahead logging~\cite{hewitt1976implementation} ensures crash recovery; our WAL applies this to agent context, preventing loss of corrections during memory compaction. Design-by-contract~\cite{meyer1997object} inspires our VBR protocol: agents verify outputs before claiming completion. Constrained policy optimization~\cite{arnold2017constrained} and sycophancy research~\cite{sharma2023sycophancy} motivate our ADL protocol for persona drift detection. LLM cost concerns~\cite{marr2023cost} drive our VFM protocol, which tracks cost-value ratios to improve routing decisions.

\subsection{Blockchain for AI Agents}

Blockchain enables trustless coordination~\cite{buterin2014ethereum, swan2018blockchain}. DIDs~\cite{spencer2015decentralized} provide verifiable agent identity; Goertzel~\cite{goertzel2017agi} envisions autonomous agent economies. \evoclaw{}'s ClawChain integrates these concepts: agents have DIDs for attribution, a genome marketplace for sharing evolved configurations, and reputation-weighted governance for mutation proposals.

\subsection{Edge AI and Lightweight Deployment}

TinyML~\cite{tinyml} targets inference on microcontrollers but not agentic behavior. Edge computing~\cite{shi2016edge} moves computation closer to data sources. \evoclaw{} combines both: full agent capabilities in a 3.0MB binary on Raspberry Pi 1, with three-tier deployment spanning edge, server, and cloud.

\subsection{Positioning of \evoclaw{}}

Table~\ref{tab:comparison} positions \evoclaw{} relative to existing systems. To our knowledge, no existing system combines: (1) declarative agent specification via a genome, (2) hot-reloadable skills with formal consistency guarantees, (3) evolutionary mutation operators over agent capabilities, (4) tiered memory with tree-structured retrieval, (5) intelligent model routing with circuit-breaker reliability, (6) agentic tool loop for edge execution, (7) self-governance mechanisms for autonomous operation, (8) multi-tier deployment from 512MB edge devices to cloud, (9) blockchain integration for decentralized identity, and (10) production-ready implementation with 90\%+ test coverage.

