%% ========================================================================
%%  SECTION 3: SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
%% ========================================================================

\section{System Architecture}
\label{sec:architecture}

\evoclaw{} is designed around six architectural principles that guide all design decisions: genome-behavior separation, skill composability, tier-appropriate deployment, bounded resources, evolutionary pressure, and safety-first constraints. We first describe these principles, then present the overall system architecture and formal genome definition.

\subsection{Design Principles}

\subsubsection{Principle 1: Genome-Behavior Separation}

The agent's behavioral specification (genome) is strictly separated from its execution engine (runtime). The Rust binary that executes skills never changes after compilation; all behavioral variation comes from genome configuration. This separation enables:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Hot-reload:} Genome changes take effect without process restart.
    \item \textbf{Portability:} Same genome runs across architectures (x86, ARM, RISC-V).
    \item \textbf{Auditability:} Genome files can be version-controlled and reviewed.
    \item \textbf{Reproducibility:} Given the same genome and runtime version, behavior is deterministic (modulo LLM sampling).
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Principle 2: Skill Composability}

Capabilities are organized as \textit{skills}—self-contained modules with defined interfaces, typed parameters, and resource bounds. Skills compose additively: enabling skill $A$ and skill $B$ gives the combined capabilities of both, without interference. This composability enables:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Incremental deployment:} Start with minimal skills, add more as needed.
    \item \textbf{Isolation:} Skill failures don't cascade to other skills.
    \item \textbf{Evolution:} Individual skills can evolve independently.
    \item \textbf{Reuse:} Skills developed for one agent transfer to others.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Principle 3: Tier-Appropriate Deployment}

Agents deploy across three tiers—edge, server, and cloud—with capabilities appropriate to each tier's resources:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Edge (512MB--4GB RAM):} Local skill execution, hot/warm memory, MQTT communication.
    \item \textbf{Server (4GB--32GB RAM):} Full skill suite, all memory tiers, LLM orchestration.
    \item \textbf{Cloud (unlimited):} Sandboxed execution, ephemeral compute, persistent memory in Turso.
\end{itemize}

The genome format is identical across tiers; only resource constraints change.

\subsubsection{Principle 4: Bounded Resources}

Context windows, memory usage, and computational budgets are explicitly bounded regardless of interaction history:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Core memory:} 5KB cap, rewritten not appended.
    \item \textbf{Tree index:} 2KB cap, restructured not grown.
    \item \textbf{Context per turn:} 8--15KB typical, never unbounded.
\end{itemize}

An agent running for five years should use the same resources as one running for five days.

\subsubsection{Principle 5: Evolutionary Pressure}

Every agent faces continuous fitness evaluation. Parameters that improve fitness are retained; those that don't are mutated. Evolution is not optional—it's the default operating mode. Agents that don't evolve stagnate; agents that evolve improve.

\subsubsection{Principle 6: Safety-First Constraints}

Safety constraints are hard-coded in the genome as inviolable bounds that evolution cannot modify:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Max loss:} Financial agents cannot exceed maximum drawdown.
    \item \textbf{Blocked actions:} Certain operations (withdraw, delete, sudo) can be permanently blocked.
    \item \textbf{Allowed assets:} Trading agents restricted to specified instruments.
    \item \textbf{Rate limits:} Agents cannot exceed action frequency bounds.
\end{itemize}

These constraints are the ``walls'' that define safe behavior; everything else is ``water'' that can flow toward fitness.

